posts.cooked:

posts.name: gcschmit
posts.cooked: We had an issue with PhotonLib last night; hard to know if it is the same as what you are experiencing. We were using v2024.1.2. It appears that version no longer exists in their repository and, as a result, unless the necessary files have already been downloaded locally, they cannot be found and the build fails. To fix this, we deleted photonlib.json from vendordeps and reinstalled the vendor dep.

posts.name: Hannah
posts.cooked: We haven’t installed the vendordep previously, so I don’t think that should be our problem. We used the installation link from their website , could you please send me the link that you used for installing?

posts.name: gcschmit
posts.cooked: We used the same link from their web site. You do need to build in order for the packages to be downloaded. Did you run “WPILib: Build Robot Code” after installing the vendor dep?

posts.name: Chris Gerth
posts.cooked:
Yes, this is intentional.

Early releases this year were extremely bloated, and should not generally be used. Since it’s still early in the season, the team opted to remove the broken releases. Latest ones have fixed the issues.

posts.name: gcschmit
posts.cooked: I get it. It was just challenging for students to debug why the code would build on one laptop and not the other yesterday.

posts.name: Hannah
posts.cooked: Yes we did run build. We tried installing the library for some other projects and they were all successful, it seemed that the issue was specific to a certain repository.

posts.name: Hannah
posts.cooked: There might have been an issue with our file paths. We deleted the local project and made a clone of the uploaded repository then tried installing the library again, and this time it worked.

posts.name: Matt
posts.cooked: And by bloated we mean “it would brick a roborio v1”

posts.name: billbo911
posts.cooked: Out of curiosity,  and a tiny bit of laziness,  can you post the correct path to use for the PV .json file?
